            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this invoice factoring calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool models a standard
                <strong>recourse invoice factoring</strong> arrangement where
                you sell an invoice to a factor, receive an upfront advance, and
                then receive the remaining reserve (minus fees) when your
                customer pays.
              </p>

              <h3>Key inputs</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Invoice amount</strong> – the face value of the
                  invoice you are factoring.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Advance rate</strong> – the percentage of the invoice
                  the factor pays you upfront (e.g., 80–90%).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Factoring fee rate (per 30 days)</strong> – the
                  discount fee charged for each 30-day period the invoice is
                  outstanding.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Expected days until customer pays</strong> – how long
                  it usually takes your customer to pay the invoice.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Extra flat fees</strong> – any additional charges such
                  as wire fees, setup fees, or minimum fees.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Formulas used</h3>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>1. Advance amount</strong></p>
                <p>Advance = Invoice amount × Advance rate</p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>2. Time factor (in 30-day periods)</strong>
                </p>
                <p>Periods = Days outstanding ÷ 30</p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>3. Discount fee</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Discount fee = Invoice amount × Fee rate per 30 days × Periods
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>4. Total fees</strong></p>
                <p>Total fees = Discount fee + Extra flat fees</p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>5. Reserve and reserve release</strong>
                </p>
                <p>Reserve (before fees) = Invoice amount − Advance</p>
                <p>
                  Reserve released at payment = Reserve (before fees) − Total
                  fees
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>6. Net cash received</strong></p>
                <p>Net cash = Advance + Reserve released at payment</p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>7. Effective APR (approximate)</strong>
                </p>
                <p>Periodic rate = Total fees ÷ Advance</p>
                <p>APR ≈ Periodic rate × (365 ÷ Days outstanding) × 100%</p>
              </div>

              <p>
                The APR calculation is an approximation that assumes you
                effectively “borrow” the advance amount for the number of days
                the invoice is outstanding. It is useful for comparing factoring
                with other financing options such as term loans or lines of
                credit.
              </p>

              <h2>Interpreting the results</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Upfront advance</strong> – improves your immediate
                  cash flow and helps cover payroll, inventory, or other
                  expenses.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total factoring fees</strong> – the true dollar cost
                  of using the factor for this invoice.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Reserve released at payment</strong> – the remaining
                  cash you receive when your customer pays.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Net cash received</strong> – total cash you end up
                  with from the invoice after all fees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Effective APR</strong> – annualized cost of the
                  factoring arrangement, based on the advance amount and time
                  outstanding.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Typical ranges in the market</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Advance rate:</strong> 70–95% (higher for strong,
                  low-risk customers).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fee rate per 30 days:</strong> roughly 1–5% depending
                  on risk, volume, and industry.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Payment terms:</strong> usually 30–90 days, but actual
                  payment behavior can be longer.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>When invoice factoring can make sense</h2>
              <p>Invoice factoring can be a good fit when:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You have
                  <strong>slow-paying but creditworthy customers</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You need cash quickly for
                  <strong>payroll, inventory, or growth</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You do not yet qualify for a traditional bank line of credit.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You want to <strong>outsource collections</strong> and credit
                  checks to a factoring company.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p>
                However, the effective APR can be high compared with bank loans.
                Always compare offers and understand:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Whether fees are <strong>flat</strong> or
                  <strong>tiered by time</strong> (e.g., 2% for the first 30
                  days, 0.5% every 10 days after).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Any <strong>minimum volume</strong> commitments or termination
                  fees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Whether the arrangement is <strong>recourse</strong> (you
                  cover non-payment) or <strong>non-recourse</strong> (factor
                  takes more risk).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>What is invoice factoring?</h3>
              <p>
                Invoice factoring is a financing method where you sell your
                unpaid invoices to a factoring company at a discount. The factor
                advances a percentage of the invoice now and collects payment
                from your customer later. When the customer pays, the factor
                sends you the remaining reserve minus their fees.
              </p>

              <h3>How is this different from invoice financing?</h3>
              <p>
                In <strong>invoice financing</strong> (or invoice discounting),
                you typically borrow against your invoices but remain
                responsible for collections. In <strong>factoring</strong>, the
                factor usually takes over collections and may notify your
                customers. The cost structure can be similar, but legal and
                operational details differ.
              </p>

              <h3>Why is the APR so high compared with the fee rate?</h3>
              <p>
                Factoring fees are often quoted as a
                <strong>flat percentage per 30 days</strong>. When you annualize
                that cost and consider that you only receive part of the invoice
                as an advance, the effective APR can be much higher than the
                nominal fee rate. This calculator makes that cost transparent.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this calculator for tiered fee structures?</h3>
              <p>
                This version assumes a
                <strong>single fee rate per 30 days</strong>. For simple tiered
                structures (e.g., 2% for the first 30 days, 0.5% for each
                additional 10 days), you can approximate an average rate over
                the expected payment period and enter that as the fee rate.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this calculator handle multiple invoices?</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator works on a <strong>per-invoice basis</strong>.
                For a batch of invoices, you can either:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Run the calculator for a representative invoice, or</li>
                <li>
                  Use the <strong>total invoice amount</strong> and an average
                  days-to-pay to approximate the overall cost.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-6">
                This tool is for educational and planning purposes only and does
                not constitute financial advice. Actual terms and costs depend
                on your factoring agreement and provider.
              </p>
